can anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1984 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1988 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1992 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1996 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2000 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2004 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2008 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Colorado Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Indiana Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Kansas Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Michigan Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Malden, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Denver]]\n[[Category:Prohibition Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Prohibition Party (United States) vice presidential nominees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{for|the college football player|W. Earl Dodge}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Earl Dodge\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Earl Farwell Dodge, Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1932|12|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2007|11|7|1932|12|24}}\n| death_place  = [[Aurora, Colorado|Aurora]], [[Colorado]], U.S.\n| restingplace = \n| party        = [[Prohibition Party]]\n| otherparty   = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (before 1952)\n| father       = Earl Farwell\n| mother       = Dorothy May Harris\n| spouse       = Barbara Viola Regan\n| children     = 7\n| relatives    = \n| education    = \n| signature    = \n}}\n\n'''Earl Farwell Dodge, Jr.''' (December 24, 1932 \u2013 November 7, 2007) was an American politician who served as the [[Prohibition Party]]'s chairman and presidential candidate from the [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]] to [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential elections]] and later ran with the nomination of his own faction during the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 presidential election]].\n\n==Life==\n\nEarl Farwell Dodge, Jr. was born on December 24, 1932, to Earl Farwell and Dorothy May Harris in Malden, Massachusetts. He attended school until the tenth grade and on July 20, 1951, he married Barbara Regan.<ref name=\"dodge life\" /> In 1952, he joined the [[Prohibition Party]] after attending a rally hosted by future Prohibition vice-presidential nominee Mark R. Shaw.<ref name=\"dodge life 2\"/>\n\n===Politics===\n\nFrom 1953 to 1956, he served as the executive secretary of the Massachusetts Prohibition Party and ran for Massachusetts Secretary of State in 1956. In 1956, he moved to Indiana and from 1958 to 1961, he served as the chairman of the Indiana Prohibition Party and ran for Indiana's second congressional district in 1960. From 1961 to 1962, he lived in Denver, Colorado. From 1962 to 1966, he worked for the National Christian Citizens Committee and ran for the United States Senate.<ref name=\"dodge life 2\"/>\n\nFrom 1958 to 1962, he served as the co-chairman of the Prohibition Party under [[E. Harold Munn]]. In 1967, he was appointed to the Kalamazoo Community Relations Board and served until 1970. In 1974, he was appointed to the Colorado State Elections Advisory Board. In 1979, he was selected to served as the chairman of the National Statesman Party, which the Prohibition Party had changed its name to in 1977, and served until 2003.<ref name=\"dodge life 2\"/>\n\nHe also ran for the governorship of Colorado with the Prohibition nomination in every election from 1974 to 1994 except for in 1990. In 1990, he ran in Colorado's [[1990 United States Senate election in Colorado|Senate election]] while his daughter, Karen J. Thiessen, ran for state Treasurer, his son, Calvin G. Dodge, ran for Secretary of State, and Calvin's wife, Elsi, ran for the regent of Colorado University.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47760781/the-daily-sentinel/ |title=Prohibition Party a family affair for Dodges |date=October 16, 1990 |work=The Daily Sentinel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331235155/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47760781/the-daily-sentinel/ |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |page=20 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential===\n\nDuring the [[1976 United States presidential election|1976]] and [[1980 United States presidential election|1980 presidential elections]] he was given the vice-presidential nomination of the Prohibition Party.{{cn|date=May 2020}}\n\nOn June 24, 1983, forty five delegates voted to give Dodge the presidential nomination in Mandan, North Dakota for the [[1984 United States presidential election|1984 presidential election]] and on January 3, 1984, he suffered a heart attack, but recovered.<ref name=\"dodge life\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47668222/the-bismarck-tribune/ |title=Prohibitionsts pick candidate |date=June 25, 1983 |work=The Bismarck Tribune |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330162621/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47668222/the-bismarck-tribune/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020 |page=17 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47668603/st-cloud-times/ |title='Dry' Party names presidential hopeful; wants bottle banned |date=June 25, 1983 |work=St. Cloud Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330162843/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47668603/st-cloud-times/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020 |page=17 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref name=\"dodge life 2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.prohibitionists.org/history/bios/dodge/dodge.html |title=Earl F(arwell) Dodge, our Presidential candidate in l984, l988, l992, l996 and 2000 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401005525/http://www.prohibitionists.org/history/bios/dodge/dodge.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> He appeared on the ballots in North Dakota, New Mexico, Kansas, Arkansas, and Colorado and as a write-in in Ohio and received 4,236 votes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1984&minper=0&f=0&off=0&elect=0 |title=1984 Presidential General Election Results}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1988 presidential election he was given the party's presidential nomination again and appeared on the ballot in Arkansas, Tennessee, New Mexico, and Colorado and received 8,002 votes.<ref name=\"dodge life 3\" /> During the 1992 presidential election he appeared on the ballot in Arkansas, Tennessee, and New Mexico and only received 961 votes.<ref name=\"dodge life 3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47848060/the-napa-valley-register/ |title=Anti-alcohol only part of prohibition |date=October 2, 1992 |work=The Napa Valley Register |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.today/KzWT3 |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |page=16 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> During the 1996 presidential election he appeared on the ballot in Colorado, Arkansas, Tennessee, and Utah and received 1,298 votes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47850210/the-miami-herald/ |title=Who's Running And Where |date=October 23, 1996 |work=The Miami Herald |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143917/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47850210/the-miami-herald/ |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |page=151 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nFrom June 28 to June 30, 1999, around thirty delegates attended the national convention in Bird-in-Hand, Pennsylvania and nine voted to give Dodge the presidential nomination against eight voting for Gary R. Van Horn and the vice-presidential nomination to W. Dean Watkins.<ref name=\"dodge life 2\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47818072/lancaster-new-era/ |title=Prohibitionists congregate in Bird-in-Hand |date=July 2, 1999 |work=Lancaster New Era |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401222730/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47818072/lancaster-new-era/ |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |page=10 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> He attempted to win the [[2000 United States presidential election in Utah|Independent American Party]] presidential nomination to receive ballot access in Utah, but was defeated by [[Constitution Party (United States)|U.S. Taxpayers' Party]] presidential nominee [[Howard Phillips (politician)|Howard Phillips]] and in the general election he only appeared on the ballot in Colorado and received 208 votes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47818510/the-daily-herald/ |title=Colorado man enters race for president |date=March 20, 2000 |work=The Daily Herald |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401223425/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47818510/the-daily-herald/ |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |page=3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=34618 |title=UT US President - IAP Primary}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=2000&minper=0&f=0&off=0&elect=0 |title=2000 Presidential General Election Results}}</ref>\n\n===2004 and 2008 presidential campaigns===\n\nDuring his tenure as chairman of the party he was criticized by members for his financial actions. He avoided paying the Social Security tax on money earned through his involvement in the Prohibition Party by laundering it through the National Prohibition Foundation.<ref name=\"dodge life\"/> During Earl Higgerson's ten years as treasurer Dodge refused to allow him to see the party's account books, donor lists, sign checks, or know of actions taken by Dodge on his account.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.alcoholproblemsandsolutions.org/earl-dodge-perennial-prohibition-party-candidate/ |title=Earl Dodge (Perennial Prohibition Party Candidate) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145115/https://www.alcoholproblemsandsolutions.org/earl-dodge-perennial-prohibition-party-candidate/ |archive-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In 1999, he sold the party's headquarters for $119,500 saying that he would use the money to build one on his property, but was alleged to have kept the money for himself and moved the party's headquarters to tool shed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2013/6/13/1215754/-The-hilarious-travails-of-the-Prohibition-nbsp-Party |title=The hilarious travails of the Prohibition Party |date=June 13, 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331112252/https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2013/6/13/1215754/-The-hilarious-travails-of-the-Prohibition-nbsp-Party |archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, members of the party opposed to him met at a condo in Tennessee and promoted him to chairman [[emeritus]], as a polite way of firing him according to [[James Hedges]]. During the 2004 presidential election their faction nominated [[Gene Amondson]] under the Concerns of People ballot line while eight delegates from his faction, twenty five delegates according to Dodge, of the party gave him its presidential nomination at his home in Lakewood, Colorado.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47723235/the-los-angeles-times/ |title=The Worst Year for Prohibition Since 1933? |date=September 19, 2004 |work=The Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331111302/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47723235/the-los-angeles-times/ |archive-date=March 31, 2020 |page=17 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.alcoholproblemsandsolutions.org/prohibition-party-the-oldest-third-party/ |title=Prohibition Party \u2013 The Oldest Third Party in U.S.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47671893/south-florida-sun-sentinel/ |title=Candidates teetotally committed to cause |date=September 20, 2004 |work=South Florida Sun Sentinel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330172634/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47671893/south-florida-sun-sentinel/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020 |page=6 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> In the general election he appeared on the ballot in [[2004 United States presidential election in Colorado|Colorado]] and received 140 votes while Amondson received 1,944 votes from Colorado and [[2004 United States presidential election in Louisiana|Louisiana]].\n\nOn June 12, 2007, members of his faction from three states met in a church in Arvada, Colorado where they nominated him for president and Howard Lydic, who received the vice-presidential nomination in 2004, for vice-president.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ballot-access.org/2007/06/13/prohibition-party/ |title=Prohibition Party |date=June 13, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330175449/http://ballot-access.org/2007/06/13/prohibition-party/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On November 7, Dodge was waiting to board a flight en route from [[Denver International Airport]] to [[Pennsylvania]], when he suddenly collapsed due to a [[cardiac arrhythmia]] and was taken to the [[University of Colorado Hospital]] where he died.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2007/11/08/presidential-candidate-was-launching-his-7th-run/ |title=Presidential candidate was launching his 7th run |date=November 8, 2007 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330151920/https://www.denverpost.com/2007/11/08/presidential-candidate-was-launching-his-7th-run/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Following Dodge's death Howard Lydick worked to unite the two factions of the Prohibition Party behind Gene Amondson before Lydick's own death on August 5, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ballot-access.org/2008/03/01/prohibition-party-factions-unite-on-a-single-presidential-candidate/ |title=Prohibition Party Factions Unite on a Single Presidential Candidate |date=March 1, 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330175218/http://ballot-access.org/2008/03/01/prohibition-party-factions-unite-on-a-single-presidential-candidate/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ballot-access.org/2008/08/28/howard-lydick-dies/ |title=Howard Lydick Dies |date=August 28, 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330175027/http://ballot-access.org/2008/08/28/howard-lydick-dies/ |archive-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n\n{{hidden begin|toggle=left|title=Earl Dodge electoral history}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title = 1956 Massachusetts Secretary of State election<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=546403 |title=MA Secretary of State 1956 |date=January 15, 2018}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n|candidate  = '''[[Edward J. Cronin]]''' (incumbent)\n|votes      = '''1,196,746'''\n|percentage = '''53.40%'''\n|change     = +2.22%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Republican Party (United States)\n|candidate  = Richard I. Furbush\n|votes      = 1,025,295\n|percentage = 45.75%\n|change     = -2.43%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Prohibition Party\n|candidate  = Earl Dodge\n|votes      = 10,030\n|percentage = 0.45%\n|change     = -0.03%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Socialist Labor Party of America\n|candidate  = Lawrence Gilfedder\n|votes      = 9,181\n|percentage = 0.41%\n|change     = -0.17%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Independent (politician)\n|candidate  = Write-ins\n|votes      = 5\n|percentage = 0.00%\n|change     = +0.00%\n}}\n{{Election box total|\n|votes     = '''2,241,257'''\n|percentage = 